      "learned": "Students learned that theoretical probability is defined as P(E) = (number of favourable outcomes in E) ÷ (total number of equally likely outcomes in S), and that this formula applies only when all outcomes are equally likely. They learned to construct sample spaces using: (1) lists, (2) two-way tables, and (3) simple tree diagrams. Students also learned that the sum of probabilities of all outcomes in a sample space equals 1, and that P(E') = 1 − P(E), where E' is the complement of event E. Key vocabulary: theoretical probability, equally likely, sample space, complement.",
