      "learned": "Students learned that two events A and B are mutually exclusive if they cannot both occur in the same trial, formally expressed as A ∩ B = ∅ and therefore P(A ∩ B) = 0. Consequently, for mutually exclusive events: P(A ∪ B) = P(A) + P(B). Students also learned that mutually exclusive events are NOT necessarily complementary — complements are always mutually exclusive, but mutually exclusive events need not be complements. Key vocabulary: mutually exclusive, intersection, union, Venn diagram, complement versus mutually exclusive distinction.",
      "explained": "Teacher should use the Venn diagram as a persistent visual throughout this lesson and refer back to it during Lesson 6 (Addition Law). Mandazi context: 'A customer cannot simultaneously buy the last plain mandazi AND the last coconut mandazi in a single purchase — these events are mutually exclusive.' Pedagogical note: A critical misconception is that students assume all pairs of events are mutually exclusive. Use cold-calling (minimum 3 students) to test non-obvious cases, e.g., 'Event A: customer spends more than Ksh 20. Event B: customer buys 3 mandazi. Are these mutually exclusive?' Allow 45-second think time before taking responses."
