      "learned": "Students learned the Addition Law of Probability: P(A ∪ B) = P(A) + P(B) − P(A ∩ B). They learned that subtracting P(A ∩ B) corrects for double-counting outcomes that belong to both events. Students recognised the mutually exclusive case from Lesson 4 as the special case where P(A ∩ B) = 0, reducing the law to P(A ∪ B) = P(A) + P(B). They practised applying the formula in both directions — finding P(A ∪ B) given the other three values, and finding P(A ∩ B) given P(A ∪ B), P(A), and P(B). Key vocabulary: addition law, union, intersection, double-counting, general addition rule.",
